Pro Tools 2022.12
ExportMix 
Deprecated:
since Pro Tools 2025.06, use the version with the CId_ prefix
CId_ExportMix 

Renders all or part of the session to one or more files.

Export Mix (Bounce Mix) can export an entire mix, including sub-mixes, to multiple file formats without having to create extra dedicated audio tracks in the session for bus recording. Different options and settings are available depending on the selected FileType. The options are organized in sections including Audio, Video, Location, and Dolby Atmos. Here's a breakdown of how the sections are used for each FileType:

  • WAV
    1. has no Video section
    2. has a unique field called DeliveryFormat (only shown if Interleaved is selected as the file format and there are multiple mix sources)
  • AIF
    1. has no Video section
  • MP3
    1. has no Video section
    2. does not allow multiple mix sources
    3. does not allow mix sources greater than 0
    4. does not allow specifying Bit Depth value (always a 16Bit)
    5. Sample Rate is limited to 48k and 44.1k
    6. Import after Bounce is not available
  • MXF OPAtom
    1. has no Video section
    2. File format is multi-mono
    3. Bit Depth is only 16Bit and 24Bit
    4. Sample Rate is limited to 48k and 44.1k
    5. Pad to frame boundary is hard-coded to ON
  • WAV (Dolby Atmos ADM BWF)
    1. has no Audio section
    2. has no Video section
    3. has Dolby Atmos section (unique to this format)
    4. has FFOA (bool) default to False
    5. if FFOA is true then there's an option to enter TimeCode value
      1. TimeCode value will match the session frame rate
      2. Frame rate will always be 23.976 and 30 non-drop (if Frame rate is 60 -> it will still be 30)
    6. has Embed Program-level Metadata
  • None (No file, dry-run) - this file "type" is used to do a dry run of an export so plug-ins can monitor the export for things like loudness metering, or an export from a renderer plug-in. The only fields that are used are:
    1. mix_source_list
    2. offline_bounce
    3. start_time/end_time
Request body type
ExportMixRequestBody

Export an MP3 file, using a bounce preset.

Request body JSON example
{
"preset_path": "/Users/username/Documents/Pro Tools/Pro Tools Presets/Bounce/bounce_preset_1.ptpreset",
"file_name": "file_name",
"file_type": "EMFType_MP3",
"location_info": {
"file_destination": "EM_FD_Directory",
"directory": "/Users/username/export_folder/",
"import_after_bounce": "TB_False"
},
"audio_info": {
"export_format": "EF_Interleaved",
"bit_depth": "Bit16",
"sample_rate": "SR_44100",
"pad_to_frame_boundary": "TB_False",
"delivery_format": "EM_DF_FilePerMixSource"
},
"video_info": {
"include_video": "TB_False"
},
"offline_bounce": "TB_True",
"mix_source_list": [{
"source_type": "Bus",
"name": "Bus 1"
},
{
"source_type": "Bus",
"name": "Bus 1-2"
}],
"start_time": {
"location": "00:00:10:00",
"time_type": "TLType_TimeCode"
},
"end_time": {
"location": "00:00:12:00",
"time_type": "TLType_TimeCode"
},
"audio_encoding_options": {
"encoding_options_mp3": {
"bit_rate": "MP3EOCBRate_320kbps",
"quality": "MP3EOQuality_Highest"
}
}
}
Note
From 2025.06 on, pass an empty encoding_options field to suppress the encoding options dialog and use defaults.

A dry-run that generates no-file.

Request body JSON example
{
"file_type": "EMFType_None",
"offline_bounce": "TB_True",
"mix_source_list": [{
"source_type": "Bus",
"name": "Bus 1"
},
{
"source_type": "Bus",
"name": "Bus 1-2"
}],
"start_time": {
"location": "00:00:10:00",
"time_type": "TLType_TimeCode"
},

"location": "00:00:12:00",

}

Since
Pro Tools 2023.12
GetSessionIDs 
Deprecated:
since Pro Tools 2025.06, use the version with the CId_ prefix
CId_GetSessionIDs 

Provides originId, instanceId and parentId of the current opened session:

  • originId is the main ID of the session (or project), and it remains the same in all variations of the session through Save As, Save Copy In, etc.
  • instanceId is unique for each session variation. In a new/original session file, the instanceId is equal to originId. When variants are introduced via Save As, Save Copy In, and several others, instanceId is set to a new unique ID.
  • parentId is set to the instanceId of the source session for sessions based off of a previous session. For new/original sessions, the parentId is set to zeros. That means parentId is equal to originId for first-generation variants, and is different for second and later generation variations.
Response body type
GetSessionIDsResponseBody
Request body JSON example
{
"origin_id": "{00000000-2a000000-086ed1e0-94ef763d}",
"instance_id": "{00000000-2a000000-086ed1e0-94ef763d}",
"parent_id": "{00000000-00000000-00000000-00000000}"
}

CId_PollEvents 

Streams real-time events from Pro Tools to the client.

This RPC runs indefinitely without a typical end condition. It does not accept input arguments, relying on other methods for event system configuration. Each InProgress struct with the event is considered a new event.

Only one active connection is allowed per PTSL session. If a new call is made within the same session, the polling is transferred to the new connection, terminating the previous one if active.

The method runs immediately, bypassing the command queue.

The method is not affected by the timeout mechanism.

The method does not suppress Pro Tools UI alerts.

See the article for more details on how to use the event system.

Response body type
PollEventsResponseBody
Response body JSON example
{
"event": {
"event_id": "EId_SessionOpened",
"event_data_json": ""
}
}
:Utility Commands:

CId_GetTrackControlInfo 

Return information about controls on a track.

Note
Defined but not yet implemented

Provide a way to query for information about one or more track controls.

Use track_id to select the track. If it is empty all tracks are queried.
Or multiple tracks can be listed and queried.

Use TrackControlId to specify a filter for which controls to query. Any values provided
in the control_id parameter can be used to filter which controls to query. Empty fields
match everything.

In response the value range and number of steps for the control are returned. For
each control the control_id is also defined. For pan controls, this will give you
the pan space that a pan control is operating in.

CId_SetTrackControlBreakpoints 

Sets a value on a target track control.

Use TrackControlId to specify whether you are targetting track volume, panning, LFE level, or an insert plug-in. Volume and pan can be either on the main output or a send.

In a TrackControlBreakpoint the time to place the value at is paired with the value itself. A single value can be passed in to set the default.
Or multiple values can specify a series of automation breakpoints. A value at time zero must always be included.
Any existing values for the control are replaced by those from this call. Values can be either floating point or integers, depending on the needs of the control. Use CId_GetTrackControlInfo to get the allowed range of values.

Request body type
SetTrackControlBreakpointsRequestBody
Request body JSON example
{
"track_id": "{00000000-2a000000-22db75e3-61ea7379}",
"control_id": {
"section": "TSId_MainOut",
"type": "TCType_Volume"
}
"value": [
{
"time": {
"location": "0",
"time_type": "TLType_Samples"
},
"value": 1.0
},
{
"time": {
"location": "10000",
"time_type": "TLType_Samples"
},
"value": 0.5
}
],
}

CId_InstallMenuHandler 

This command can be used to install a custom menu item into Pro Tools menus.

The client provides the menu label and where in the app to put the menu item.

Once a menu item is installed, the client must be running CId_PollEvents to recieve notifications when the item is selected by the user. CId_PollEvents will notify the client that a EId_MenuItemSelected event has happened. The response will include the menu_item_id that is returned by this function to differentiate among multiple installed menu handlers. But it is opaque and no other assumptions should be made about its value.

The command auto-subscribes to EId_MenuItemSelected events, as if CId_SubscribeToEvents were called.

Use CId_UninstallMenuHandler to clean up.

Request body type
InstallMenuHandlerRequestBody
Request body JSON example
{
"menu_info": {
"menu_area": "MArea_Import",
"menu_label": [
{"locale": "en", "string": "Menu label in English"},
{"locale": "zh-cn", "string": "Menu label in Simplified Chinese"}
]
}
}
Response body type
InstallMenuHandlerResponseBody
Response body JSON example
{
"menu_item_id": "opaque.menu.item.id"
}
:Utility Commands:
:Private APIs:
Since
2025.10

◆ TimelineLocationType

enum TimelineLocationType

Types for global timeline times.

Since
Pro Tools 2024.10
Enumerator
TLType_Unknown 
TLType_Samples 

Integer number of samples, based on the session's current sample rate (e.g., 48,000 samples per second).

Session start is always sample 0.

TLType_Ticks 

Integer number of ticks - musical time, divided as 960,000 ticks per beat, with a beat length depending on the session's tempo ruler (e.g., 120 beats per minute) and the meter map (beat equals quarter note, eigth note, etc.).

Starting tick offset is 1,000,000,000,000 instead of zero.

TLType_Frames 

Integer number of video frames, based on the session's current frame rate (e.g., 30 frames per second).

TLType_MinSecs 

Clock time in the format, MM:SS.mmm (minutes, seconds, milliseconds).

TLType_TimeCode 

Timecode in the format HH:MM:SS:FF (hours, minutes, seconds, frames), based on the session's current frame rate and session start timecode location.

TLType_BarsBeats 

Musical time location, in the format, BARS|BEATS[|TICKS], where BARS and BEATS are 1-based values, and TICKS (optional) are based on the MIDI standard of 24 ticks per beat.

All are based the session's tempo (e.g., 120 beats per minute), meter (e.g., 4/4), and song start position (which locates where 1|1 is, in samples, relative to session start).

TLType_FeetFrames 

Feet and frame FEET+FRAMES, based on the session's current frame rate (e.g., 30fps) and the constant of 16 frames per foot.

TLType_Seconds 

Floating point number of seconds.

enum PanControlParameter

Parameters of pan control that can be automated.

A subset of parameters are allowed in given PanSpace.

Since
Pro Tools 2025.10
Enumerator
PCParameter_Unknown 

Tech-only value.

Don't use it in requests.

PCParameter_Pan 

Basic 1-D panning for mono and stereo formats.

-1.0 to 1.0, left to right panning, 0.0 being center. Available in PSpace_Stereo.

PCParameter_PosFront 

The "Position Front" control for surround panning.

Available in pan space PSpace_Surround2d.

PCParameter_PosRear 

The "Position Rear" control for surround panning.

-1.0 to 1.0. Available in pan space PSpace_Surround2d.

PCParameter_PosFrontRear 

The "Position Front/Rear" control for surround panning.

-1.0 to 1.0. Available in pan space PSpace_Surround2d.

PCParameter_CenterPct 

The "Center Percent" control for surround panning.

-1.0 to 1.0. Available in pan space PSpace_Surround2d.

PCParameter_DivFront 

The "Divergence Front" control for surround panning.

-1.0 to 1.0. Available in pan space PSpace_Surround2d.

PCParameter_DivRear 

The "Divergence Rear" control for surround panning.

-1.0 to 1.0. Available in pan space PSpace_Surround2d.

PCParameter_DivFrontRear 

The "Divergence Front/Rear" control for surround panning.

-1.0 to 1.0. Available in pan space PSpace_Surround2d.

PCParameter_Distance 

The "Distance" control for surround panning.

Distance from center, range 0 to 1.0. Available in pan space PSpace_3dSphere2Layer and PSpace_3dSphere3Layer.

PCParameter_Azimuth 

The Azimuth control for spherical 2-layer and 3-layer panning.

Horizontal position angle, range -180.0 to 180.0, with 0 at front center. Available in pan space PSpace_3dCart2Layer and PSpace_3dCart3Layer.

PCParameter_Elevation 

The Elevation control for spherical 2-layer and 3-layer panning.

Vertical angle. In pan space PSpace_3dSphere2Layer, ranges from 0 to 90.0, with 0 at listener level, and 90.0 directly above. In pan space PSpace_3dSphere3Layer -90.0 to 90.0, with -90.0 directly below listener, 0 at listener level, and 90.0 directly above.

PCParameter_X 

The X control (of XYZ) for cartesian 2-layer and 3-layer panning.

Left-right axis, range -1.0 to 1.0. Available in pan space PSpace_3dCart2Layer and PSpace_3dCart3Layer.

PCParameter_Y 

The Y control (of XYZ) for cartesian 2-layer and 3-layer panning.

Front-rear axis, range -1.0 to 1.0. Available in pan space PSpace_3dCart2Layer and PSpace_3dCart3Layer.

PCParameter_Z 

The Z control (of XYZ) for cartesian 2-layer and 3-layer panning.

Vertical axis. In pan space PSpace_3dCart2Layer ranges from 0 to 1.0. In PSpace_3dCart3Layer ranges from -1.0 to 1.0.

PCParameter_Size 

The object size control for cartesian/spherical 2-layer and 3-layer panning.

Range 0 to 1.0. Available in pan space PSpace_3dCart2Layer, PSpace_3dCart3Layer, PSpace_3dSphere2Layer, PSpace_3dSphere3Layer.

◆ PanSpace

enum PanSpace

The pan space in which a pan control is defined.

Sphere refers to spherical coordinates. Cart refers to cartesian coordinates. 2-layer means the upper hemisphere only. 3-layer includes the lower hemisphere, below the floor.

Compatible controls for each pan space are defined in PanControlParameter.

Since
Pro Tools 2025.10
Enumerator
PSpace_Unknown 

Tech-only value.

Don't use it in requests.

PSpace_Stereo 

The track is using legacy Pro Tools panning.

PSpace_Surround2d 

The track is using legacy Pro Tools 2-D surround panning.

PSpace_3dCart2layer 

The track is using Cartesian 2-layer 3-D panning.

With 2-layer Z runs from 0 to 1.0.

PSpace_3dCart3layer 

The track is using Cartesian 3-layer 3-D panning.

With 3-layer Z runs from -1.0 to 1.0.

PSpace_3dSphere2layer 

The track is using Spherical 2-layer 3-D panning.

With 3-layer Elevation runs from 0 to 1.0.

PSpace_3dSphere3layer 

The track is using Spherical 3-layer 3-D panning.

With 3-layer Elevation runs from -1.0 to 1.0.
